{{notability|Biographies|date=October 2014}} {{Infobox person |name = Gloria Jean Siebrecht |image = |alt = |caption = |birth_date = 1940 |birth_place = Kalispell, Montana |residence = |death_date = |death_place = |nationality = American |other_names = |known_for = amateur paleontologist |occupation = }}
'''Gloria Jean Siebrecht''' (born 1940) is an [[United States|American]] amateur [[paleontologist]] and volunteer for the [[Museum of the Rockies]], notable as the discoverer of ''[[Avisaurus |Avisaurus Gloriae]]'', which was named for her, and ''[[Piksi barbarulna]]''.
She is the sixth child of James Baily Schnee and Marie Van De Rite of [[Kalispell, Montana]]. She grew up in [[Columbia Falls, Montana]]; [[McMinnville, Oregon]]; and [[Lincoln City, Oregon]]. She graduated from [[Taft High School (Lincoln City, Oregon)|Taft High School]] in Lincoln City in 1958. She married Odell Siebrecht in 1959 and raised two sons on a farm north of [[Cut Bank, Montana]].<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Varrichio|first1=David J.|last2=Chiappe|first2=Luis M.|title=A New Enantiornithine Bird From the Upper Cretaceous Two medicine Formation of Montana|journal=Journal of Vertebrate Paleontology|date=March 14, 1995|volume=15|issue=1|pages=201–204|doi=10.1080/02724634.1995.10011219}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Varricchio|first1=David J.|title=A new bird from the Upper Cretaceous Two Medicine Formation of Montana|journal=Canadian Journal of Earth Sciences|date=2002|volume=39|issue=1|pages=19–26|doi=10.1139/e01-057|bibcode=2002CaJES..39...19V}}</ref>
As a volunteer for the Museum of the Rockies, Siebrecht spent thousands of hours on digs and in preparing fossils for display.
