{{distinguish|Access to Information}}
{{globalize|date=December 2010}}
{{Information science}}
'''Information access''' is the freedom or ability to identify, obtain and make use of [[Data|data]] or information effectively.<ref>"Information Access." Computer Sciences. . Encyclopedia.com. 28 Feb. 2017 <http://www.encyclopedia.com>.</ref>

There are various research efforts in information access which objective is to simplify and make it more effective for human users to access and further process large and unwieldy amounts of data and [[information]].A person who is searching for information uses a search engine to achieve their information hunt. These searches for information can be of a wide range.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://people.ischool.berkeley.edu/~hearst/irbook/10/node4.html | title=Modern Information Retrieval}}</ref>

Several technologies applicable to the general area are [[Information Retrieval]], [[Text mining|Text Mining]], [[Machine Translation]], and [[text categorisation|Text Categorisation]].

During discussions on free access to information as well as on [[information policy]], information access is understood as concerning the insurance of free and closed access to [[information]]. Information access covers many issues including [[copyright]], [[Open-source model|open source]], [[privacy]], and [[security]].

Groups such as the [[American Library Association]], the [http://www.aallnet.org American Association of Law Libraries], [[Ralph Nader]]'s [http://www.tap.org Taxpayers Assets Project] have advocated for free access to [[Legal research|legal information]]. The [https://web.archive.org/web/20050403183057/http://www.aallnet.org/committee/citation/ vendor neutral citation] movement in the [[legal]] field is working to ensure that courts will accept [[Case citation|citations]] from cases on the web which do not have the traditional (copyrighted) page numbers from the [[West Publishing]] company.  There is a worldwide [[Free Access to Law Movement]] which advocates free access to legal information. The Wired Magazine Article [https://www.wired.com/wired/archive/2.05/the.law.html Who Owns The Law] is an introduction to the access to legal information issue. Postsecondary organizations such as K-12 work to share information. They feel it is a legal and moral obligation to provide access (including to people with disabilities or impairments) to information through the services and programs they offer.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.washington.edu/doit/information-access-0|title=Information Access {{!}} DO-IT|website=www.washington.edu|language=en|access-date=2017-10-13}}</ref>

