[[File:Carstensz-expeditie.jpg|thumb|[[Anton Colijn]], {{ill|Frits Wissel|nl}} and Jean Jacques Dozy during the [[Carstensz expedition]] (1936) ]]
'''Jean Jacques Dozy''' (18 June 1908, in [[Rotterdam]] – 1 November 2004, in [[The Hague]]) was a [[Netherlands|Dutch]] [[geologist]].

In 1936, he participated in the Dutch [[Carstensz Expedition]] in [[Dutch New Guinea]] to explore and  climb [[Mount Carstensz]], the highest mountain of the island of [[New Guinea]]. Besides succeeding in climbing the [[Ngga Pulu|highest point at the time]] with [[Anton Colijn]] and Frits Wissel, Dozy discovered the presence of abundant copper ore in a mountain he called Ertsberg (English, "Ore mountain"). Years later this gave rise to the [[Grasberg mine|Grasberg copper mine]]. In 1939, he published an article about his find, but it was neglected due to [[World War II]]. Twenty years later, the article led to rediscovery of the Ertsberg and the development of the Ertsberg-Grasberg mine complex.

